d 'War on Terror' and the global financial crisis of 2008.Through analysis of texts drawn from literature, film, television, theatre and the visual arts (from the Europe to South East Asia, Africa to North and South America) the collection examines the ways in which the representational strategies of the gothic mode are ideally suited to an exploration of the dark side of neoliberal enterprise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExile (Punishment). 0aGothic fiction (Literary genre)xHistory and criticism. 0aGothic literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aImperialismxHistoryy19th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndigenous peoplesxPolitics and government. 0aKings and rulersxDeposition. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aPenal transportation. 4aGothic 2017. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Gothic & Romance.2bisacsh  aDracula.  aGerman postdramatic theatre.  aIn the Flesh.  aIrish artists.  aglobal economic policy.  agothic home.  ainternational gothic.  aneoliberal age.  aneoliberal gothic.  aorgan trafficking.  avampire.1 aAncuta, Katarzyna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlake, Linnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlake, Linnie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDuncan, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFahey, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGenz, Stéphanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHantke, Steffen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacfarlane, Karen E, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonnet, Agnieszka Soltysik, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMurnane, Barry, e